  issn = {17425689 (ISSN); 17425662 (ISSN)},
  doi = {10.1098/rsif.2016.0825},
  abstract = {Improved understanding of geographical variation and inequity in health status, wealth and access to resources within countries is increasingly being recognized as central to meeting development goals. Development and health indicators assessed at national or subnational scale can often conceal important inequities, with the rural poor often least well represented. The ability to target limited resources is fundamental, especially in an international context where funding for health and development comes under pressure. This has recently prompted the exploration of the potential of spatial interpolation methods based on geolocated clusters from national household survey data for the high-resolution mapping of features such as population age structures, vaccination coverage and access to sanitation. It remains unclear, however, howpredictable these different factors are across different settings, variables and between demographic groups. Here we test the accuracy of spatial interpolation methods in producing gender-disaggregated high-resolution maps of the rates of literacy, stunting and the use of modern contraceptive methods from a combination of geolocated demographic and health surveys cluster data and geospatial covariates. Bayesian geostatistical and machine learning modelling methods were tested across four low-income countries and varying gridded environmental and socio-economic covariate datasets to build 1\texttimes 1 km spatial resolution maps with uncertainty estimates. Results show the potential of the approach in producing high-resolution maps of key gender-disaggregated socio-economic indicators, with explained variance through cross-validation being as high as 74-75\% for female literacy in Nigeria and Kenya, and in the 50-70\% range for many other variables. However, substantial variations by both country and variable were seen, with many variables showing poormapping accuracies in the range of 2-30\% explained variance using both geostatistical and machine learning approaches. The analyses offer a robust basis for the construction of timely maps with levels of detail that support geographically stratified decision-making and themonitoring of progress towards development goals. However, the great variability in results between countries and variables highlights the challenges in applying these interpolation methods universally across multiple countries, and the importance of validation and quantifying uncertainty if this is undertaken. \copyright{} 2022 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {Access to resources,Access To Resources,adolescent,Adolescent,adult,Adult,Africa south of the Sahara,Africa South Of The Sahara,age distribution,Age Distribution,Article,Artificial intelligence,Artificial Intelligence,artificial neural network,Artificial Neural Network,Bangladesh,Bayes theorem,Bayes Theorem,Bayesian learning,Bayesian Learning,Bayesian network,Bayesian Network,child,Child,clinical decision making,Clinical Decision Making,computer simulation,Computer Simulation,Contraception Behavior,contraceptive agent,Contraceptive Agent,contraceptive behavior,Contraceptive Behavior,controlled study,Controlled Study,Covariates,cross validation,Cross Validation,decision making,Decision making,Decision Making,Decision support systems,Decision Support Systems,demographics,Demographics,demography,Demography,Development indicator,Development Indicator,Development Indicators,feed forward neural network,Feed Forward Neural Network,female,Female,gender disaggregated development indicator,Gender Disaggregated Development Indicator,Geo-statistics,Geographic Information System,Geographic information systems,Geographic Information Systems,geographic mapping,Geographic Mapping,Geographical variations,Geographical Variations,Geostatistical,growth disorder,Growth Disorder,Growth Disorders,Health,Health status,Health Status,health survey,Health Survey,High resolution maps,High Resolution Maps,High-resolution mapping,High-resolution Mapping,household,Household,human,Human,Humans,Interpolation,Kenya,Learning systems,Learning Systems,literacy,Literacy,low income country,Low Income Country,machine learning,Machine Learning,male,Male,Mapping,Markov chain Monte Carlo method,Markov Chain Monte Carlo Method,middle aged,Middle Aged,Neural Networks (computer),Neural Networks (Computer),Nigeria,nutritional status,Nutritional Status,population health,Population Health,Population statistics,Population Statistics,poverty,Poverty,priority journal,Priority Journal,rural population,Rural Population,sanitation,Sanitation,sensitivity analysis,Sensitivity Analysis,sex difference,Sex Difference,Sex Factors,Socioeconomic Factors,socioeconomics,Socioeconomics,spatial analysis,Spatial Analysis,Spatial interpolation method,Spatial Interpolation Method,statistics and numerical data,Statistics And Numerical Data,stunting,Stunting,Surveys,sustainable development,Sustainable Development,sustainable development goal,Sustainable Development Goal,Tanzania,uncertainty,Uncertainty,Uncertainty analysis,Uncertainty Analysis,vaccination,Vaccination,vaccination coverage,Vaccination Coverage,wellbeing,Wellbeing}
